        <div class="snippet-answer">
          <p><strong>SERP features</strong> are enhanced search result types that appear on a Google results page alongside or instead of standard blue-link organic listings. They include featured snippets, People Also Ask boxes, knowledge panels, local packs, image packs, video carousels, shopping results, and AI Overviews. Each type appears for specific query categories and has distinct qualification criteria, structured data requirements, and click-through rate implications.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="term-meta-strip">
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Category</div>
            <div class="tms-value">On-Page SEO</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Also Called</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Rich Results, Enhanced Results</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Difficulty</div>
            <div class="tms-value">Intermediate</div>
          </div>
          <div class="tms-cell">
            <div class="tms-label">Read Time</div>
            <div class="tms-value">9 min</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <p class="lede-p">Google's search results page looks very different today than it did a decade ago. The standard "ten blue links" model has been supplemented — and in many cases displaced — by a growing set of specialised result formats. Understanding which SERP features appear for which query types, and how to qualify for them, is core modern SEO knowledge.</p>

        <h2 id="what-is">What are SERP features?</h2>
        <p>SERP features are any search result element that departs from the standard organic listing format (page title + meta description + URL). Google began adding enhanced result types in the early 2010s, initially with Knowledge Panels and Shopping results. By 2026, SERP features appear on the majority of Google searches, particularly for informational and commercial queries.</p>

        <p>SERP features matter for SEO because they change the competitive landscape of a keyword. A featured snippet at position zero may draw more clicks than position 1 organic. A local pack pushes organic results so far down the page that position 1 organic may get minimal traffic. AI Overviews can answer a query entirely without the user ever clicking through.</p>

        <h2 id="types">The main SERP feature types</h2>

        <h3>Featured Snippet (Position Zero)</h3>
        <p>A featured snippet appears above the first organic result and displays a direct answer to the query, extracted from a web page. Types include: paragraph snippets (for definitional queries), list snippets (for how-to or step-by-step queries), and table snippets (for comparison queries).</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Rank in the top 10 for the target keyword, structure your content to directly answer the likely query, use concise paragraph answers (40-60 words) for definition queries, and numbered lists for step-by-step answers.</p>

        <h3>People Also Ask (PAA)</h3>
        <p>A dynamic accordion box showing related questions Google believes the searcher may also want answered. Clicking a question expands a snippet-style answer and often adds new questions to the bottom of the list.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Target question-format keywords. Include FAQ sections with clear question headings and concise answers. Use FAQ schema markup to make answer extraction easier for Google.</p>

        <h3>Knowledge Panel</h3>
        <p>A card on the right side of desktop SERPs (and prominent on mobile) that displays entity information — typically for brands, people, organisations, and locations. Knowledge panels pull from Google's Knowledge Graph and are informed by Wikipedia, Wikidata, official social profiles, and structured data.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Build entity authority through consistent NAP data, Wikipedia entries, Google Business Profile verification, and structured data. Knowledge panels are algorithmically generated — you cannot directly create one, but you can strengthen the signals that trigger them.</p>

        <h3>Local Pack (Map Pack)</h3>
        <p>A cluster of three local business listings displayed alongside a Google Maps embed for queries with local intent. The local pack appears for "near me" searches, service-area queries, and many other queries with implicit geographic intent.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Claim and fully optimise your Google Business Profile, build consistent NAP citations across directories, generate reviews, and maintain strong local SEO signals on your website.</p>

        <h3>Image Pack</h3>
        <p>A horizontal row of images from Google Images appearing mid-SERP for queries where visual results are likely useful — product searches, recipe searches, travel destinations, how-to visual guides.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Use descriptive, keyword-rich alt text on high-quality images. Include images in content on pages targeting visual-intent queries. Submit an image sitemap.</p>

        <h3>Video Carousel</h3>
        <p>A row of video thumbnails, typically from YouTube, appearing for queries where video content is likely the preferred format — tutorials, product demonstrations, music, entertainment, exercise guides.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Create YouTube videos optimised for the target keyword with strong title, description, and transcript. Use VideoObject schema on embedded videos on your site.</p>

        <h3>Shopping Results (Product Listing Ads)</h3>
        <p>A row of product images with prices and merchant names appearing for transactional product queries. These are paid placements via Google Shopping, but they occupy prominent SERP real estate that affects organic click-through rates for commercial queries.</p>

        <h3>Sitelinks</h3>
        <p>Additional links to internal pages of a website displayed beneath the main result — typically shown for branded navigational queries. Sitelinks are algorithmically awarded and cannot be directly requested, though you can demote specific sitelinks in Search Console.</p>

        <h3>AI Overviews</h3>
        <p>Introduced at scale from 2024, AI Overviews (previously called Search Generative Experience) display an AI-generated synthesised answer at the very top of the SERP for many informational queries. The answer cites multiple sources. When an AI Overview appears, it occupies substantial screen space and compresses the visibility of organic results below it.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify for citation:</strong> Produce highly authoritative, accurate, well-structured content on topics where AI Overviews trigger. Build E-E-A-T signals. Ensure your content is crawlable and clearly structured so Google can extract passages from it.</p>

        <h3>Rich Snippets</h3>
        <p>Enhanced organic listings that display additional visual elements — star ratings, review counts, price ranges, recipe details, event dates — pulled from structured data (Schema.org JSON-LD) on your page.</p>
        <p><strong>How to qualify:</strong> Implement valid Schema.org structured data for your content type. Use Google's Rich Results Test to validate. Types supported: Review, Recipe, Article, Event, Product, FAQ, How-To, and more.</p>

