        <h2 id="ctr-impact">How SERP features affect click-through rates</h2>
        <p>SERP features have complex effects on click-through rates — sometimes helping, sometimes hurting — depending on whether you occupy the feature and the feature type.</p>

        <div class="pros-cons">
          <div class="pros-card">
            <h4>Features that typically increase CTR</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>Featured snippets (when you own them)</li>
              <li>Rich snippets with star ratings</li>
              <li>Sitelinks for branded queries</li>
              <li>Local pack listings</li>
              <li>Video carousels (for video content)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
          <div class="cons-card">
            <h4>Features that typically reduce CTR</h4>
            <ul>
              <li>AI Overviews (zero-click answers)</li>
              <li>Knowledge panels (answering without clicks)</li>
              <li>Direct answer boxes for simple queries</li>
              <li>Shopping ads (capture transactional clicks)</li>
              <li>Local pack (competitors may appear instead)</li>
            </ul>
          </div>
        </div>

        <h2 id="how-to-track">How to track SERP feature visibility</h2>
        <p>Monitoring which SERP features your site appears in — and which competitors own — is part of modern keyword strategy. Tools that provide SERP feature tracking include:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Ahrefs:</strong> Shows which keywords you rank for that trigger SERP features, and whether you appear in the feature</li>
          <li><strong>Semrush:</strong> SERP features column in keyword reports; position tracking includes feature visibility</li>
          <li><strong>Moz:</strong> SERP analysis overlays show feature types per keyword</li>
          <li><strong>Google Search Console:</strong> Search result types filter in the Performance report (limited feature granularity)</li>
        </ul>

        <h2 id="mistakes">Common SERP feature mistakes</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Targeting featured snippets without ranking in the top 10.</strong> You cannot win a featured snippet if you are not already in the top 10 for that keyword. Build rank first.</li>
          <li><strong>Using structured data without earning the content quality first.</strong> Schema markup helps Google extract information, but Google will not show a rich snippet for low-quality or thin content regardless of markup.</li>
          <li><strong>Ignoring SERP features when setting traffic expectations.</strong> A keyword with 10,000 monthly searches and a featured snippet, AI Overview, and image pack may deliver far fewer organic clicks than the raw volume suggests. Always analyse the actual SERP before projecting traffic.</li>
          <li><strong>Failing to track feature ownership changes.</strong> Competitors can displace you from a featured snippet. Regular SERP monitoring catches feature losses before they show up as traffic drops.</li>
        </ul>

